{"/service/ndnp/arhi/batch_arhi_huskerdu_ver01/data/sn89051168/00393343254/1908050301/0980.xml":{"full_text":"SECTION ONI.\nPA0B8 ONE TO BIGflT.\nMEMBER OF THE HEARST NEWS SYNDICATE.\nCOL. XIV.\nPINE BLUFF, ARKANSAS, SUNDAY MORNING, MAY 3, 1908.\nNUMBER 261.\nI\nJUDGE GOULD\nPOSTPONES SALE\nSale of the Large Estate of Wijey Jones Postponed for\nThird Time\u2014Property Will Positively Be Sold July\n2\u2014Motion in Arrest of Sale Filed by Attorneys W.\nF. and C. T. Coleman an d E. J. Kerwin Representing i\nCreditors and Heirs G-ranted by Judge Gould\nSaturday at noon was the time\nscheduled for file sale of all of the\nreal estate belonging to the estate of\nWiley Jones, deceased, amounting to\nnearly seventy pieces, among which\nwere the two brick business houses\non Main street and the Jones Park\nproperty. It was to be sold to pay\noff the debts of the estate including\nthe probated claims and also claims\nthat are being contested in court. The\namount of the claims still pending and\nnot paid against the estate will reach\n$50,000. It is said by many that the\nestate is easily worth $125,000.\nAttorneys C. T. and W. F. Coleman,\nE. J. Kerwin, J. \"W. Crawford and X.\nJ. Gantt appeared before Judge James\nGould in the county court at 11 o\u2019clock\nfor the purpose of stopping the sale as\ncontemplated. In the petition filed be\nfore Judge Gould by the first three at\ntorneys who represented Monroe Ham\nilton, one of the heirs of the estate,\nand Arthur Murray and W. H. John\nson, administrator of the estate of\nJarrett, Johnson, deceased, creditors of\nthe estate, it was alleged:\nThat the sale should be postponed\nbecause due publicity was not given\nrelative to the sale and that the pub\nlic was not aware that the property\nwas to be sold. Also that T. Y. Mur\nphy, one of the three appraisers of the\nproperty, was not a disinterested\nhouseholder and appraiser, but that he\nwas deeply interested and that his\nappraisement was not impartial: that\nthe property was only appraised at\nabout fifty per cent of its real market\nvalue. Affidavits were filed to sup\nport the allegations contained in the\npetition. Another cause alleged was\nthat the present time for a sale of so\nmuch property would not redound to\nthe benefit of the creditors or the\nheirs of the estate, owing to the fact\nthat the recent financial panic which\nhas been in progress throughout the\ncountry has not ceased to exist* The\nestate was appraised at something like\n$64,000. The administrator in succes\nsion and the interests of the estate\nwere looked after by Attorneys\nWhite Althoimer and other interests\nby Austin Danaher.\nJudge Gould, after going into the\nmatter thoroughly, and hearing both\nsides to the controversy, determined\nthat the property should bring as\nmuch money as possible for the cred\nitors and the heirs, and further that\nthe appraisement should meet no ob\njections from any source. Judge\nGould accordingly granted the motion\nin arest of sale and continued the\nsale of this vast estate until July 2,\nlf*0S, at which time it will he sold\nfrom the steps of the court house at\nnoon. Judge Gould further ordered\nthat new appraisers be appointed, dis\ninterested parties, and that a new ap\npraisement be filed. The objection\nmade by counsel to the low appraise\nment in both former contemplated\nsales was due to the fact that the law\nrequires property to bring only two\nthirds of its real value, which would\nhave meant not enough money to have\npaid the probated and contested claims\nagainst the estate of Wiley Jones.\nThe estate of Wiley Jones is one of j\nthe most valuable in this section of\nthe state, especially the fine piece of\nproperty composed of thirty-seven\nacres known as Jones Park. This\nproperty was shown by affidavits of\nthe petitioners in court yesterday to\nbe estimated by some citizens to be\nWorth from $36,000 to $50,000, and the\ntwo buildings on Main street from\n$36,000 to $40,000.\n\nCleveland Is in\nSerious State\nHearst News Special to the Graphic.\nNew York, May 2.\u2014Notwithstanding\nthe report given out today by Mrs.\nCleveland from Lakewood that former\nPresident Grover Cleveland is slowly\n1 recovering, news was received here\nthat the sick man is in a very serious\ncondition and that physicians praeti\njcally despair of his life. The opinion\njat Lakewood is that the gravity of the\npatient\u2019s illness is being kept from\n'the public.\nCannon Will Whip\nThem in Line\nHearst News Special to the Graphic.\nWashington, May 2.\u2014Speaker Can\nnon has determined that there shall be\n[currency legislation in this session, i\nThe party whip is to be applied and\nI every Republican member will be\ni forced to toe the mark. A conference\n,on the currency bill will be held next\nTuesday night. The revised Vreeland\nbill will be-presented to the confer\n1 once for indorsemnt- It is the pres\nent programme of the House leaders\nto force this bill through. It provides\nan emergency currency based on the\n[assets of national banks.\n_ i\nMISS BLODGETT TO\nLECTURE HERE\nMiss Mary X. Blodgett of Detroit,\nMich., a Bible teacher of note, will\ndeliver the first of a series of Bible\nlessons Sunday afternoon from 4 to,\n5 o\u2019clock at the First Baptist church, i\nThis begins her course on Women\nof the Bible.\" She will continue this\ncourse on each Sunday in May. Ev\nery one is cordially invited to be pres\nent. On Tuesday, Miss Blodgett will\ncommence a course in methods of Bi\nble study for ladies. These lessons\ni will continue on Wednesday. Thurs\nday and Friday from 4 to f> o'clock\nland will be at the First Presbyterian\nchurch.\nj Miss Blodgett is a graduate of the\nMoody Bible School in Chicago, and\nhas had wide experience in her work.\nThis is Miss Blodgett\u2019s second vis\nit to our city, her many firends wel\ncome her most gladly. Many have\ncause to remember her stay among us\nfour years ago. We urge all who cat\nto attend these Bible lessons.\nMr. and Mrs. J. Walter \u2022Ferguson,\nwho have spent the winter in Tucson,\nArizona, will arrive Saturday to\nspend a few days with Mr. and Mrs.\nArthur L. Ferguson on their way to\ntheir home in Fayetteville\u2014Ft. Smith\nNgws Record.\nDreyfus\u2019 Store Talk\nThat Bargain Table\nDid you see it yesterday? It\nwas again full of real, season\nable bargain offerings.\nThere were handsomely trim\nmed Lawn Waists. Priced $1.25\nthat sold for ..85c\nThere were those Novelty Strip\ned Petticoats. Priced at $1.00\nthat went for ..85c\nThere was that fine Courtauld\nEnglish Voile that sells at $1.00\nand $1.25. You could buy it yes\nterday at per yard.g5c\nFull yard wide black Taffeta\nSilk could be had there at -35C\nThen there were pretty Muslin\nGowns embroidery trimmed,\nmarked $1.25 and sold at.. -85c\nI Men's Columbia $1.25 Shirts\nwent at ..-85c\nKEEP YOUR EYE OX THE\nTABLE.\nDreyfus\u2019 Dept. Store\nDYNAMITED DY\nEJECTED TRAMP\nBurlington Passenger in Montana Completely Wrecked\nby Bombs Supposed to Have Been Placed by Tramps\n\u2014Hand Grenades Hurled at Express Car, Which\nMay Furnish Robbery Clue\u2014Fireman Has Flesh\nBlown From Body\u2014Head Engine Lifted Bodily\nFrom Track and Second Turns Over.\nButte, Mont.. May 2.\u2014Eastbound\nBurlington train No. G, due in Butte\nat 11:1.0 o'clock last night, was dyna\nmited about a mile west of the North\nern Pacific station at 11:37 o\u2019clock.\nThe explosion caused the first or\nhelper engine to leave the rails, but it\nplowed along for a few hundred feet\nwithout turning over. The second en\ngine crashed into the bank south of\nthe track'a few car lengths front\nwhere the explosion occurred and\nturned over.\nEvery person on the train has been\naccounted for except Engineer Bussy\nof the second engine, who is supposed\nto be buried under his locomotive. Carl\nMange, who was riding on the blind\nbaggage, was taken from the mass of\ntimbers under which he was buried.\nHis arm and leg ere broken. Fire\nman George Ehle of the second engine\nwas severely scalded. Both were hur\nried to the hospital.\nThe mail car was hurled on its side\nand wrecked. A cold storage fish car\nwas smashed into kindling wood. Only\nthe front trucks of the express car left\nthe rails. The baggage car was also\nderailed, and only the Pullmans re\nmained on the track.\n-o\nProbably Work oi Tramps.\nInvestigation by the sheriff and po\nlice into the dynamfting of the east\nbound Burlington train, which left\nthis city at 11:30 o'clock last night,\nand by which the train was almost\ncompletely wrecked, Fireman Ehle and\none other being scalded and otherwise\ninjured, I lie helper engine and regu\nlar engine together with all cars but\nthe Pullman leaving the track, is be\nlieved to have been the work of a\ntramp seeking revenge for being eject\ned from the train.\nExpress Messenger J. 1!. Vatentiu\nwas seriously cut by a flying grenade.\nIlis escape from death in the car is\nconsidered remarkable. A clear ac-,\ncount of the explosion and wreck was\ngiven by Engineer W. Lenzie of the1\nhelper engine.\n\u201cWe were ten minutes behind time,\u201d\nsaid he, \"and we were running at the\nrate of about forty miles per hour on J\na line perfectly straight and we had\nclear track.\n\u201cSuddenly there was a terrific re\nport and my engine was lifted clear of\nthe (rack, hut it quickly settled on the\nties along which it ran for about\nthree hundred feet. I applied the\nbrakes but not before the coupling\nhad broken between my engine and\nthe one following. After applying air\nI shouted to my fireman, John Doreing,\nto jump and we both dropped to the\nground as the engine came to a stand\nstill.\n\u201cAs soon as 1 realized the situation\nI hastened to the scene of the wreck\nand found the second engine turned\n.over on its side. A moment later I ran\nj into Fireman George Ehle. He was\nwalking about wildly with arms and\nj hands terribly shattered and skin ac\nj tually falling from his body. Ambu\nlances quickly responded and he was\nhastened to a hospital.\u2019\u2019\nDESERTS HOME FOR\nMYSTERIOUS CULT\nI\nI\nI^ifayette, Ind., May 2\u2014President\nAVinthrop Ellsworth Stone of Perdue\nUniversity confirmed last night the re\nport that his \"wife had withdrawn from\nthe world, including her husband and\nfamily, to pursue the mystic teaching\nsupposed to be imported from India.\nHe and his two sons are heart-brok\nen and would eagerly welcome her\nback but they are unable to reach her.\nThe circumstances were laid by\nPresident Stone before the board of\ntrustees of the university with his res\nignation but the board voted unani\nmously to retain President Stone.\nThree years ago there was organized\nin Lafayette a class in so-called Yoga\nPhilosophy. Many women and some\nmen in the college joined the class,\nwhich became quite a fad with certain\nhighly educated people. It taught the\ncomplete power of Yoga and involved\n\u201cwithdrawal\u201d or separation from kin-i\ndred and friends.\nThe last heard from President\nStone\u2019s wife she was in Germany.\nLAFAYETTE LODGE\nNO. 101, K. OF P.\nhast Monday night was the most\npoorly attended meeting the lodge has\nheld in a long time. The Carnival\nand other attractions drew the mem\nbers away from the lodge. Although\nthe third rank was scheduled for this\nmeeting, and two candidates on hand,\nyet, after consulting with the candi\ndates, it was decided to delay the work\nuntil next Monday night as it takes\nat least twenty-four members to con\nfer this rank in the amplified form\ncorrectly, and the candidates choosing 1\nto \u201cget their money\u2019s worth,\u201d consent-!\ned. Visiting Knights will receive a1\ncordial welcome.\n__ I\nMr. and Mrs. Ed Aaronson left yes- j\nterday for St. Louis, where they will1\nspend several weeks with relatives and\nthen go to New York, where they will\ntake passage on the steamer Lusitania,!\nfor Liverpool and other points in the\nOld World. i\nWhy Not Be Comfortable\nGes a Vudor Porch Shade, a Vudor Hammock or a Porch Swing in\nreed or mission; Porch Chairs or settees in reed, bent wood or\nmission, and a Crex Rug\u2014then you can live on the porch.\nA LAWN SWING,\nA REFRIGERATOR OR ICE BOX,\nA STONE FILTER.\nand some of the Other seasonable goods we can sell you, then you\nwill cease to simpl yexist, but can LIVE throughout the summer.\nUNION FURNITURE CO. 1\n817-319 Main Street.\nBIG JOINT SMOKER\nFRIDAY NIGHT\nEnthusiasm again characterized the\nmeeting of the local member- of the\nArkansas Travelers last night at the\nHotel Jefferson, when further plans\nwore perfected with a. view to secur\ning the 1909 meeting of the Travelers\nfor I\u2019ino Bluff, when they pull off\ntheir annual festivities at Fort Smith\nin June.\nPresident W. N. Trulock, the presi\ndent of the local organization, pre\nsided and Meyer Solmson acted as sec\nretary. The attendance was large, two\nof the interested persons being Pres\nident P. P. Byrd of the Pine Bluff\nBoard of Trade and E. A. Schicker,\nowner and proprietor of the Arlington\nhotel. Both Mr. Byrd and Mr. Schick\ner made addresses. Mr. Byrd assured\nthe Travelers that the Board of Trade\nwill do everything in its power to aid\nthem in securing the next meeting for\nPine Bluff. Personally, he said, he\nwould donate his energies in that di\nrection. Mr. Schicker also expressed\nsimilar sentiments, declaring that\nPine Bluff should have the convention\nand that it would take the combined\nefforts of our business people and\nTravelers to bring it here next year.\nHe was with the movement heart und\nsoul, lie said, and would do everything\npossible to help give Pine Bluff the\n1909 meeting.\nA\u2019arious committees reported last\nnight, among them being the trans\nportation committee, of which Mayor\nAV. L. Toney is chairman. Mayor\nToney reported that a special rate\nhad been secured for Pullman quar\nters on the special train. A rate of $9\neach way was granted the local del\negation by the Pullman company.\nA letter was read which had been\nprepared by President Trulock by di\nrection of the Travelers hero and a\ncopy was seiu to each of 7f>0 Travelers\nover the state the past week. The\nletter follows:\nMy Dear Sir: The Arkansas Trav\nelers will soon meet at Fort Smith\nto celebrate their annual outing. This\nno doubt will be the largest gathering\nof the organization in its history, and\na gpod time is assured to all. The cit\nizens of Fort Smith are making exten\nsive preparations for the entertain\nment of this convention, and there is\nevery indication that they are going to\ngive you the time of your life Our\nvarious organizations, such a.; the\nBoard of Trade and the banking in\nstitutions of our city, our merchants\nand our citizens in general desire this\nconvention to meet with us next year.\nWe believe that the traveling men owe\nthe next convention to Pine Bluff, and\nwill discharge their obligation.\nPine 'Bluff is well organized and\nmaking strenuous efforts to capture\nthe meeting for 1909 and ha3 every\nreason to feel that its efforts will\nmeet with success, iu which event we\npromise you the best time of your life\nWe sincerely trust that you wt'.l at\ntend the convention at Fort Smith\nthis year and in the selection of the\nconvention city for 1909 will give your\nhearty support for Pine Bluff.\nIn any event, trusting to see you in\nthe beautiful city of Fort Smith iu\nJune and with good wishes for the or\nganization and every individual mem\nber, we are sincerely yours,\nW. N. Trulock, Chairman; Guy Leflar,\nSecretary, Pine Bluff Post Ark.\nTravelers.\nPine Bluff Board of Trade, by P. P.\nByrd, President; J. L. Caldwell,\nSecretary.\nW. P. Lindsay, First Vice President\nArkansas Travelers.\nW. L. Toney, Mayor.\nTom Green Sr. reported having\nheard from the Stephens and Fordyce\nbands and E. B. Bloom also informed\nthe Travelers of a possibility of se\ncuring the Russellville band. The\ncommittee on music was given further\ntime in which to report.\nA. W. Nunn of the special commit\ntee appointed to confer with the\nBoard of Trade to arrange for a joint\nsmoker to be given at the Hotel Jef\nferson, reported that the matter would\nbe taken up by the Board of Trade\nMonday at its regular meeting. It is\nplanned to give the smoker Friday\nnight of this week and all of the\nbusiness people of the city will be\ninvited to attend, with the Travelers.\nButtons bearing the words, \u201cA. T.\nPine Bluff 1909,\u201d were distributed\namong those present and they will be\ndistributed by them throughout the\ncity and state. E. B. Bloom, chair\naiaa of the campaign en.umiih-e. ,s\ninstructed to plan an order for\nand pennant canes.\nHarry B. 3Olmson, chairnnui of ttie\ncommittee on uniforms, reported hav\ninS secured a largo number of orders\nfor them and all who have not given\nin their measures, efc., are rerjuested\nto Jo so at once.\nOn motion of I*. 1>. Byrd the trans\nportation committee was instructed to\nmake reservations for those who will\ngo to the Border City on a special\ntrain of Pullman cars over the Cotton\nBelt and Rock Island roads, via lit\ntie Rock. Already more than a hun\ndred members have pledged them\nselves to attend the big convention,\nand many of thm will be accompanied\nby their ladies.\nTrain Splinters\nAuto-5 Unhurt\nllearst News Special to the Graphic.\nNew York, May 2.\u2014The most re\nmarkable automobile accident on rec\nord occurred here this afternoon at\nLittle Ferry, N. J., when a West Shora\nexpress train whizzing at fifty miles\nan hour struck a motor car on its\nside and smashed it to splinters, but\ndid not seriously hurt any of the five\noccupants. Those in the car were\nChas. Taylor, Mrs. Taylor, Miss Dor\nothy Cornell Taylor, Mr. and Mrs.\nWalter Gilson, all New Yorkers.\nBig Trio Controls\nWashington Life\nHearst News Special to the Graphic,\nj New York, May 2.\u2014-Edward A. Whit\ntier, formerly agent for the AVashlng\ni\nton Life Insurance Company, in a\nsuit for $20,000 damages against that\ncompany charged Thos. F. Ryan, Levi\nP. Morton, Harry Payne Whitney and\nother insurance men with withdraw\ning all deposits over $500 from coun\ntry to produce a financial panic and\nproduce a \u201cbear\" market in Wall\nstreet and bring disgrace upon\nRoosevelt. It is alleged that the trio\ncontrolled the Washington Life and\nthat its directors are mere dummies.\n\u2014Raymond Thompson, the 15 year\nold white boy who was recently con\nvicted of a grand larceny charge in\nthe Jefferson circuit court, was yes\nterday taken to the State Reform\nSchool at Little Rock and not to the\nstate prison- Thompson, George Re\nbecca and Harvey McCool were all\ntaken to the Reform School.\nDirt Cheap\nCan furnish Dirt and make\nprompt deliveries to any part\nof city. Dirt taken from East\nSecond and West Sixth avenue.\nOld Phone 585.\nNo delays in delivery.\nMen\u2019s $3.50 Oxfords\nWe are showing a line of\nMen\u2019s Oxfords In a medium\npriced shoe that have as much\nstyle and snap as most $5.00\nshoes.\nThey are made on a neat\nswing last, either patent or gun\nmetal calf. Our price \u2022\u2022\u25a0$3.50\nLEVERENZ'TRLLOCK\nSHOE CO.\nNo. 220\nMain Street,\ni","height":"28908","width":"20848"}}
